03963nam a22005535i 9780520919303DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19981998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209193037 a10.1525/97805209193032doi  a(DE-B1597)648999  a(OCoLC)1419789589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aStarrett, Gregory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPutting Islam to Work :bEducation, Politics, and Religious Transformation in Egypt /cGregory Starrett; ed. by Gregory Starrett. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (370 p.) :b3  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Studies on Muslim Societies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPART I -- t1 Creating an Objcct -- tPART II -- t2 Education and the Management of Populations -- t3 The Progressive Policy of the Government -- tPART III -- t4 Learning about God -- t5 The Path of Clarification -- t6 Growing Up: Four Stories -- tPART IV -- t7 State of Emergency -- t8 Broken Boundaries and the Politics of Fear -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe development of mass education and the mass media have transformed the Islamic tradition in contemporary Egypt and the wider Muslim world. In Putting Islam to Work, Gregory Starrett focuses on the historical interplay of power and public culture, showing how these new forms of communication and a growing state interest in religious instruction have changed the way the Islamic tradition is reproduced.During the twentieth century new styles of religious education, based not on the recitation of sacred texts but on moral indoctrination, have been harnessed for use in economic, political, and social development programs. More recently they have become part of the Egyptian government's strategy for combating Islamist political opposition. But in the course of this struggle, the western-style educational techniques that were adopted to generate political stability have instead resulted in a rapid Islamization of public space, the undermining of traditional religious authority structures, and a crisis of political legitimacy. Using historical, textual, and ethnographic evidence, Gregory Starrett demonstrates that today's Islamic resurgence is rooted in new ways of thinking about Islam that are based in the market, the media, and the school.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aStarrett, Gregory, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020927540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091930340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919303/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles